version: 1
display_name: VCFE-9X-000108 - The ESX host must enforce an unlock timeout of 15 minutes after a user account is locked out.
global_description: |-
  By enforcing a reasonable unlock timeout after multiple failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute forcing, is reduced. Users must wait for the timeout period to elapse before subsequent logon attempts are allowed.
osfinger: []  # API/proxy-managed control; not tied to a minion OS grain
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFE-9X-000108
  srg:
    - SRG-OS-000329-VMM-001180
  cci:
    - CCI-002238
  nist:
    - AC-7 b
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_vsphere_esx:
    type: custom
    desc: The ESX host must enforce an unlock timeout of 15 minutes after a user account is locked out.
    control_id: VCFE-9X-000108
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      From the vSphere Client, go to Hosts and Clusters.

      Select the ESX Host >> Configure >> System >> Advanced System Settings.

      Select the "Security.AccountUnlockTime" value and verify it is set to "900" or more and not "0".

      or

      From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESX host, run the following command:

      Get-VMHost | Get-AdvancedSetting -Name Security.AccountUnlockTime

      If the "Security.AccountUnlockTime" setting is less than 900 or is set to 0, this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      By enforcing a reasonable unlock timeout after multiple failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute forcing, is reduced. Users must wait for the timeout period to elapse before subsequent logon attempts are allowed.
    remediation: |-
      From the vSphere Client, go to Hosts and Clusters.

      Select the ESX Host >> Configure >> System >> Advanced System Settings.

      Click "Edit". Select the "Security.AccountUnlockTime" value and configure it to "900".

      or

      From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESX host, run the following command:

      Get-VMHost | Get-AdvancedSetting -Name Security.AccountUnlockTime | Set-AdvancedSetting -Value 900
